entry.title: media/muxers: introduce MuxerAdapter.
entry.content:
With the advent of the MP4 muxer, we now need to centralize

sample scheduling previously present in WebmMuxer so that

we don't duplicate the logic into the Mp4Muxer as well.



This CL introduces a new class MuxerAdapter to which a

media::Muxer is passed. This class assumes the old Muxer API

and the Muxer interface is vastly simplified.



WebmMuxer and Mp4Muxers are adjusted, as well as the

MediaRecorderHandler. All relevant unit tests have also

been adapted in accordance with the logic change in this CL.



Bug: 1475338

entry.title: Change GPU watchdog timeout init factor from 2 to 1 on Windows
entry.content:
When we first set the GPU watchdog timeout length for the gpu

initialization on Windows, we doubled the timeout length due to some

slow library loads on Windows. Now we pause the watchdog before

loading libraries. We should be able to switch back to the normal

timeout length.



The current histogram shows we have far less watchdog

kills in GPU initialization than in normal work flow. That's a

hint we can make the timeout shorter for the GPU initialization.



Add inlining constexpr variable definitions in headers outside of

classes to avoid unnecessary copies of the constant. See

https://abseil.io/tips/168 for more details.

entry.title: ChromeOS: don't always restart net service when kerberos enabled
entry.content:
Since the network service sandbox and kerberos are incompatible,

a sandboxed network service has to be restarted unsandboxed when

an admin enables kerberos (at runtime) on ChromeOS.



Chrome was mistakenly restarting the network service the first time

an admin enabled kerberos, even if the network service was unsandboxed

(i.e. NetworkServiceSandbox feature is disabled). This was unnecessary

and tickled another bug (see crbug.com/1494567).



So the fix is to set `g_network_service_will_allow_gssapi_library_load`

to true for the duration of the process if the network service sandbox

is disabled by feature state.

An upcoming CL [1] will move the

`PrefetchServingPageMetrics` recording from

`PrefetchDocumentManager::DidStartNavigation()`

to `PrefetchService::all_prefetches_`-based.

`PrefetchService::all_prefetches_`,

`all_prefetches_` and thus will be reflected to

`PrefetchServingPageMetrics` even after [1].



This should be fine as the new behavior is the same as

the existing behavior of other prefetches ineligible

for other non-delegate reasons.

entry.title: [Extensions] Add a new scripts_internal API
entry.content:
Note: forked from emiliapaz's work on

https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/4932785.



This CL introduces a new `scripts_internal` API type that defines a

structure, scripts_internal::SerializedUserScript, that can be used

to represent serialized user scripts from different types. This wires

up the ExtensionUserScriptLoader to use this new type instead of

api::content_scripts::ContentScript.



Now, when loading scripts from the StateStore, we will convert them

into the new SerializedUserScript type before converting them into

UserScript objects. When writing values to the StateStore, we store

them as SerializedUserScripts. This new type allows us to avoid the

hack we have in place for storing `id` on the serialized script

value and enables us to add more functionality unique to certain

script types in the future.



Other notable changes:

* We now check the ID for validity. Previously, we only checked it

for its presence, which meant we could crash if we found an invalid

ID and have undefined behavior if the ID corresponded to a type we

didn't expect (like a static content script in the dynamic script

store).

* Because this will require a full migration of the state store entries,

this removes the (incorrect) UMA logging for ID updates. A follow-up

will add UMA logging for the conversion to the new type.



This also adds a test for going from the old structure to the new

structure, ensuring scripts are properly loaded and preserved.



This CL should have no developer or user perceptable change.



Followup CLs will use this new serializable type in more areas,

allowing us to reduce duplicate code between the three sites of script

parsing.

entry.title: Replace WebContents::SetIgnoreInputEvents
entry.content:
Currently, `WebContents::SetIgnoreInputEvents` takes a boolean that

directly enables / disables input events. This is problematic for

cases in which multiple requests to ignore input exist at once.



This change replaces it with `IgnoreInputEvents()`, which returns a

ScopedClosureRunner. Input events are blocked until all outstanding

closures have been run. As a bonus, this also prevents leaving the

WebContents in a blocked state unintentionally.
